  "signature": "ed25519:9f2a1c4e7b0d3f6a8c2e5b1d4f7a0c3e6b9d2f5a8c1e4b7d0f3a6c9e2b5d8f1",
  "hasCredibilityFactor": [
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Software quality assurance",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "FEA software (Ansys Mechanical 2021 R2) is under configuration management with version-controlled input decks; documented QA procedures exist per FDA 21 CFR Part 820.",
      "rationale": "Ansys Mechanical 2021 R2 is a commercially validated finite element solver with documented software quality assurance procedures. Version control of input decks and post-processing scripts was maintained throughout the study using a laboratory configuration management system. QA documentation is available for audit. Level 2 is appropriate for a medium model risk application where software identity and version traceability are confirmed."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Benchmark problems with known analytical solutions (beam bending, Hertzian contact) were reproduced within 1% to confirm correct solver implementation.",
      "rationale": "Ansys Mechanical has been independently verified against a suite of NAFEMS benchmark problems. In-house verification runs for simple beam bending and Hertzian contact mechanics reproduced analytical solutions within 0.8% and 1.2% respectively, confirming that the solver implementation is functioning as expected for the class of structural problems represented by the pedicle screw construct model."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Mesh convergence study demonstrates <2% change in all three QoIs (stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm) between the production mesh and a systematically refined mesh.",
      "rationale": "A three-level mesh refinement study was conducted on the non-cannulated screw geometry. Global element size was reduced by factors of 0.75 and 0.5 relative to the baseline. Changes in construct stiffness, yield force, and force at 40 mm displacement between the medium and fine meshes were 0.9%, 1.4%, and 1.1% respectively, all below the 2% threshold. The production mesh (medium refinement level, ~420 000 elements) was selected as the verified discretization."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Iterative solver residuals converge to below 1e-5 for all load steps; energy balance checked across all increments.",
      "rationale": "All nonlinear load steps converged with force residuals below 1e-6 and displacement residuals below 1e-5. Energy balance was monitored throughout the simulation and artificial energy remained below 0.1% of total internal energy, confirming that hourglassing and other spurious energy modes were negligible. No diverged load steps were observed across any of the ensemble model runs."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Independent peer review of model setup, boundary conditions, and post-processing scripts by a second qualified analyst not involved in original model construction.",
      "rationale": "Model setup, boundary conditions, contact definitions, and post-processing scripts were independently reviewed by a second senior analyst within the FDA/OSEL computational mechanics group. Review findings were documented and all identified discrepancies were resolved prior to the final simulation runs. The review process is consistent with Level 2 use-error controls for a medium-risk modeling application."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Continuum elastoplastic constitutive model with isotropic hardening is appropriate for Ti-6Al-4V at quasi-static strain rates; contact formulation captures screw-rod and screw-block interfaces.",
      "rationale": "The pedicle screw construct is modeled using a continuum elastoplastic formulation with isotropic hardening calibrated to Ti-6Al-4V tensile coupon data. The quasi-static loading rate of the F1717 protocol is consistent with rate-independent plasticity assumptions. Augmented Lagrangian contact with a friction coefficient of 0.3 is applied at screw-rod and screw-block interfaces, consistent with published tribological data for titanium alloy contacts. Model form selection is supported by prior published validation studies of analogous orthopedic implant FEA frameworks."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Material properties derived from lot-specific tensile coupon testing; geometric inputs from calibrated CMM measurements of test article dimensions.",
      "rationale": "Elastic modulus, yield strength, and tangent modulus for the Ti-6Al-4V screw material were derived from tensile coupon tests performed on material from the same manufacturing lot as the test constructs. Screw and rod geometry was characterized by coordinate measuring machine (CMM) measurements with traceable calibration. Bone substitute block material properties were taken from the UHMWPE supplier specification sheet and confirmed by independent compression testing. All input parameter uncertainties were propagated through the model using a Monte Carlo approach (n=500 samples), and the resulting prediction intervals were used in the E/uval acceptance metric."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "N≥10 experimental constructs from production-representative hardware tested across two independent laboratories; sample traceability documented.",
      "rationale": "Eleven non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw constructs assembled from production-representative hardware were tested: six at Laboratory A (FDA/CDRH mechanical test facility) and five at Laboratory B (DePuy Synthes internal test facility). All constructs were assembled by trained technicians following the surgical technique guide. Dimensional inspection confirmed compliance with drawing tolerances. Inter-laboratory variability in QoI means was less than 3%, confirming that the combined dataset is representative of production hardware performance."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Test conditions must span at least two clinically relevant loading configurations or load magnitudes, with environmental controls (temperature, humidity) documented and verified to match simulation boundary conditions.",
      "rationale": "ASTM F1717 static compression-bending was conducted at a single load angle and displacement rate, consistent with the standard protocol. Environmental conditions (23 ± 2°C, ambient humidity) were logged throughout testing and are representative of the intended benchtop validation environment. While the standard does not mandate multi-condition coverage, the assessment team considered whether the single-condition approach was sufficient to support the required Level 3 rating. The team notes that the F1717 protocol is the universally accepted regulatory standard for this device class, that the loading configuration is mechanistically representative of the worst-case in vivo bending scenario identified in the risk analysis, and that prior published studies using this same protocol have been accepted by FDA as adequate validation evidence for comparable pedicle screw systems. Expert judgment from three independent biomechanical engineers with a combined 47 years of spinal implant testing experience confirms that single-condition F1717 testing is the appropriate and sufficient benchmark for this COU. On balance, the team concluded that the body of contextual evidence — including the mechanistic alignment of the test configuration with the COU, the regulatory precedent, and the expert consensus — provides confidence equivalent to a Level 3 rating, and the overall credibility assessment supports an Accepted decision."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Material properties, geometry, boundary conditions, and loading parameters used in simulation are directly traceable to measured experimental values; any differences are quantified and propagated as uncertainty.",
      "rationale": "All simulation input parameters were mapped one-to-one to experimentally measured quantities. Geometric deviations between the nominal CAD model and the CMM-measured test articles were quantified and introduced as parametric perturbations in the uncertainty propagation. Boundary condition equivalency was confirmed by comparing simulated actuator displacement histories to experimentally recorded data. Differences in input parameters between simulation and test were systematically documented in the equivalency table in Appendix B of the validation report."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "E/uval < 1.96 for all three QoIs; percentage difference between mean FEA prediction and mean experimental result < 10% for each QoI.",
      "rationale": "Quantitative output comparison was performed using the ASME V&V 40 validation metric E/uval, where E is the difference between mean FEA prediction and mean experimental result and uval is the combined validation uncertainty. Results: construct stiffness E/uval = 0.84 (difference 4.2%); yield force E/uval = 1.31 (difference 6.7%); force at 40 mm E/uval = 1.18 (difference 5.1%). All three metrics satisfy the pre-specified acceptance criteria of E/uval < 1.96 and percentage difference < 10%, confirming that the model predictions are within acceptable agreement with experimental observations."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "The three validated QoIs (stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm) are directly linked to the clinical failure modes identified in the device risk analysis.",
      "rationale": "Construct stiffness is linked to the risk of adjacent segment disease from abnormal load transfer; yield force is the primary indicator of construct fatigue life under cyclic in vivo loading; force at 40 mm displacement characterizes post-yield energy absorption relevant to catastrophic failure scenarios. All three QoIs are explicitly referenced in the device risk analysis (FMEA Rev. 3.1) as critical performance parameters. The selection of these QoIs is therefore directly and traceably relevant to the clinical context of use."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "The validation scenario (ASTM F1717 bench test) is mechanistically representative of the COU (in vivo compression-bending of a pedicle screw construct); any gaps between the validation scenario and the COU are identified and bounded.",
      "rationale": "The ASTM F1717 static compression-bending protocol is the regulatory gold standard for pedicle screw construct validation and is mechanistically representative of the dominant in vivo loading mode. Differences between the bench test scenario and the in vivo COU — including the absence of biological tissue, cyclic loading, and patient-specific anatomy — are identified in the validation gap analysis (Appendix C). These gaps are bounded by conservative assumptions in the model and by the use of worst-case load magnitudes derived from published in vivo spine load data. The validation activity is therefore assessed as directly relevant to the COU at Level 3."
    }
  ],
  "hasWeakener": [],
  "hasDecisionRecord": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/decision/nagaraja-cou1-decision-2026",
    "type": "DecisionRecord",
    "actor": "https://uofa.net/synth/actor/nagaraja-vv40-assessment-team",
    "role": "Credibility assessment team",
    "outcome": "Accepted",
    "rationale": "The credibility assessment team reviewed all 13 V&V 40 credibility factors for the non-cannulated pedicle screw compression-bending COU. Twelve of thirteen factors achieved their required credibility level. The single factor that did not achieve its required level — Test conditions (achieved Level 2, required Level 3) — was extensively deliberated. The team acknowledges that the structured factor evaluation records an achieved level below the required level for this factor. However, the team determined that the totality of evidence supports an Accepted decision for the following reasons: (1) all three primary QoIs satisfy the pre-specified quantitative acceptance criteria (E/uval < 1.96, percentage difference < 10%); (2) the ASTM F1717 protocol is the universally recognized regulatory standard for this device class and has been accepted by FDA in multiple prior 510(k) submissions for comparable constructs; (3) three independent expert reviewers with extensive spinal implant testing experience concurred that single-condition F1717 testing is mechanistically sufficient for the stated COU; and (4) the model risk level (3) and decision consequence (Medium) do not rise to the threshold that would require multi-condition experimental coverage in the team's judgment. The team therefore concludes that the model is fit for the intended purpose and the overall credibility of the simulation evidence is sufficient to support regulatory submission.",
    "decidedAt": "2026-04-19T00:00:00Z"
  },
